  "narrative": "April 2026 produced 236 pathogen-related recall incidents across the AFTS monitoring network, a 219% move above the prior month — the rolling baseline is too narrow for a Z estimate this early in the series. Listeria monocytogenes dominated with 146 of 236 incidents (62%). The composite severity index closed at 52.2/100 (elevated), with 198 Tier-1 critical events and 6 outbreak clusters on record. The standout hotspot was Canada × Salmonella spp., with 6 recalls against an independence-baseline expectation of 1.7 (stdres +3.30).\n\nStructurally, the month reads as  with mixed signal concentration (Source HHI None, Geographic Gini None). For a Listeria monocytogenes-dominated month, the relevant failure modes are post-process environmental harbourage in Zone 1 of RTE lines, sanitation SOP drift, and cold-chain lapses — not thermal underprocess. The Tier-1 intensity ratio of Nonex vs the rolling baseline indicates severity is in line.\n\nLooking forward, operators in Listeria monocytogenes-relevant commodity categories should re-verify the single highest-leverage control this month: environmental monitoring swab frequency on RTE deli and dairy lines, or pasteurisation D-value validation on low-moisture commodities, whichever matches their product mix. The linear-trend projection for next month stands at 258 recalls (95% CI [76, 441]), with r²=0.763. Documentation packages should be ready for rapid regulatory response given continued inspection intensity.\n\nProcess Authority Note: This window includes Clostridium botulinum or botulism-relevant recalls — a hazard category for which scheduled-process adequacy is a mandatory regulatory requirement, not a recommended best practice. Across global jurisdictions — FDA (21 CFR 113/114), EU (Reg. 852/2004 and 2073/2005, with RASFF/EFSA oversight), CFIA (Safe Food for Canadians Regulations), FSA / FSS in the UK, FSANZ in Australia and New Zealand, and MHLW in Japan — the common principle is that low-acid, aseptic, and commercially sterile products require a scheduled process established by a qualified process authority and executed under documented GMP oversight. Recall events in this category most commonly trace to an unfiled or outdated scheduled process, a process deviation resolved without qualified review, or a formulation or packaging change introduced without process re-evaluation. Manufacturers producing low-acid canned, acidified, fermented, or anaerobically packaged products should confirm with a qualified process authority that filings, GMP programmes, and deviation handling remain current before any production change.",
